'''Chen Qimei''' ({{zh|t=陳其美|s=陈其美|p=Chén Qíměi}}; 17 January 1878 – 18 May 1916) was a Chinese revolutionary activist, close political ally of [[Sun Yat-sen]], and early mentor of [[Chiang Kai-shek]]. He was as one of the founders of the [[Republic of China (1912–1949)|Republic of China]], and the uncle of [[Chen Guofu]] and [[Chen Lifu]].
Born in [[Wuxing District|Wuxing]], [[Zhejiang]], [[China]], he went to [[Japan]] for studies in 1906, and there joined the Chinese [[Tongmenghui]]. Befriended by fellow Zhejiang native [[Chiang Kai-shek]], in 1908, Chen brought Chiang into the [[Tongmenghui]].
In 1911, after the [[Wuchang Uprising]], Chen's forces occupied [[Shanghai]]. He was then made military governor of the region. He fled to Japan with [[Sun Yat-sen]] upon the failure of the revolution against [[Yuan Shikai]]'s dictatorship. They subsequently formed the [[Chinese Revolutionary Party]], which later became the [[Kuomintang]], or the Chinese Nationalist Party. As he was returning to Shanghai for another round of revolution, Yuan had him assassinated on May 18, 1916.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chang |first1=Nelson |last2=Chang |first2=Laurence |year=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UI3_-7dMPIoC&pg=PA197 |title=The Zhangs from Nanxun |publisher=CF Press |page=197 |isbn=9780692008454}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Bergère |first=Marie-Claire |year=1998 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vh7M1u4IGFkC&pg=PA268 |title=Sun Yat-sen |publisher=Stanford University Press |page=268 |isbn=9780804740111}}</ref> The assassination was believed to have been carried out by [[Zhang Zongchang]], a general loyal to Yuan.<ref>{{cite book |last=Patricia Buckley |first=Ebray |year=2009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CUcdH6opOlcC&pg=PA374 |title=Chinese Civilization, A Sourcebook |edition=2nd |publisher=Simon and Schuster |page=374 |isbn=9781439188392}}</ref>
Chen is perceived as one of the early revolutionary heroes and one of the founding fathers of the [[Republic of China (1912–1949)|Republic of China]]. He was also the eldest member of which later came to be known as the [[Chen Family]], one of the four most powerful and influential families at the time. The university which had been originally named after him has become a part of today's [[Fudan University]] and [[Zhejiang University]] after the [[Chinese Civil War]]. A monument of him is located in [[Huzhou]], [[Zhejiang]], [[China]].
==See also== *[[Republic of China (1912–1949)|Republic of China]]
