{{Infobox award | name = The [[Webby Awards]] | image = | imagesize = 150px | caption = [[Webby Awards]] logo | description = "Excellence on the Internet including Websites, Interactive Advertising, Online Film & Video and Mobile content."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webbyawards.com/about/|title=About|publisher=Webby Awards|accessdate=2008-06-01}}</ref> | presenter = [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]] | country = | year = 1997<!--The entry process started from 1996 and the finalists were awarded in 1997 --> | website = {{URL|www.webbyawards.com}} }}
This is a list of the people, companies or websites that won the annual [[Webby Awards]] presented by the [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]]. The Webby Awards have been dubbed the "internet's highest honor".<ref>{{cite web|title=Here Are The Winners Of The 21st Annual Webby Awards|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40411830/here-are-the-winners-of-the-21st-annual-webby-awards|publisher=Webby Awards|accessdate=27 April 2017}}</ref>
<!-- the awards given in 1994-6 were monthly awards by web.org and not listed because it was a different type of award--> ==1997==<!-- compiled from http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/winners-1997.php --> {{main|1997 Webby Awards}} 1997 was the first year of the annual Webby Award event, which was the first-ever nationally televised awards ceremony devoted to the Internet. 700 people attended the event on March 6, 1997 at Bimbo's Night Club in [[San Francisco, California]]<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=2007-01-03|title=Webbys 2.0|author=Rachel Rosmarin|date=June 9, 2006|url=https://www.forbes.com/technology/2006/06/09/webby_internet_award_cx_rr_0609webby.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061215025202/http://www.forbes.com/technology/2006/06/09/webby_internet_award_cx_rr_0609webby.html|archivedate=2006-12-15}}</ref> Whereas in later years the panelists were official members of [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]], in 1997 the awards were chosen and given by [[International Data Group|IDG]]'s ''The Web Magazine'', which appointed a panel to judge the competition.<ref name="Carolyn Said">{{cite news|accessdate=2008-01-08|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|title=The Woman Behind the Webbies:S.F., N.Y. woo Web award impresario Tiffany Shlain|author=Carolyn Said|date=July 30, 1998|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/1998/07/30/BU52646.DTL}}</ref>
==1998== {{main|1998 Webby Awards}} The 1998 Webby Awards were held on March 6, 1998 at the [[Palace of Fine Arts|San Francisco Palace of Fine Arts]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,3879/article.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120911143230/http://www.pcworld.com/article/id,3879/article.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=September 11, 2012 |publisher=PC World |date=March 31, 1998 |title=The Best of the Web: The 1998 Webby Award Winners }}</ref> and were the first event ever to be broadcast live via the Web in [[Anaglyph 3D|3D]].<ref>{{cite news|publisher=PC World|title=1998 Webby Awards: Like the Oscars, Only Funny:San Francisco awards show honors the best Web sites in 19 categories.|author=Glenn McDonald|date=March 10, 1998|url=http://www.pcworld.com/printable/article/id,6187/printable.html}}</ref> The "People's Voice" awards, chosen by online poll, received 100,000 cumulative votes that year.
''The Web'' magazine, which was hosting the awards, was closed down by its parent company [[International Data Group|IDG]] shortly before the awards, and the ceremony continued thereafter under the management of [[Tiffany Shlain]], who IDG had hired in 1996 to coordinate the awards.<ref name="Carolyn Said"/> The [[International Academy of Digital Arts and Sciences]] was constituted that year as the judging panel for the awards, continues to do so as of the 2007 awards.
==1999== {{main|1999 Webby Awards}} The 1999 Webby Awards were held on March 18, 1999 at the Herbst Theater ([[War Memorial Opera House (San Francisco)|War memorial Opera House]]) in San Francisco, with a post-award party at [[San Francisco City Hall|City Hall]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/TECH/computing/05/12/webby.awards/index.html |publisher=CNN |accessdate=2008-01-02 |title=Buchanan, goofiness mark Webby Awards ceremony |date=May 12, 2000 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230053328/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/TECH/computing/05/12/webby.awards/index.html |archivedate=December 30, 2007 }}</ref> That year, Mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]] lobbied to move the ceremony to [[New York City]], but San Francisco Mayor [[Willie Brown (politician)|Willie Brown]] convinced the organization to remain in San Francisco by promising city support. The event was noted for the famous incident in which a representative of [[Jodi.org]], which had won in the arts category, called the event participants "Ugly corporate sons-of-bitches" in his acceptance speech and tossed his trophy to the audience.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Computergram International|title=Usual Suspects Takes Webbies in Five Words or Less|date=March 22, 1999|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0CGN/is_1999_March_22/ai_54170019| author=Rachel Chalmers }}</ref> In 1999 the Webby Awards asked [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]] to help it tabulate and ensure security for the "People's Voice" winners, chosen by online voting.<ref>{{cite news|title=PricewaterhouseCoopers Address On-Line Balloting Issues for Webby Awards|publisher=Business Wire|date=March 17, 1999|accessdate=2008-01-03|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1999_March_17/ai_54127102}}</ref>
