==2005== {{main|2005 Webby Awards}} Honorees at 9th Annual Webby Awards included:<ref>[http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?season=9 9th Annual Webby Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100124153336/http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current.php?season=9 |date=2010-01-24 }}</ref> *''Webby Lifetime Achievement Award'': Former Vice President [[Al Gore]] in recognition of the role he played in the development of the Internet over the past three decades<ref name=usatoday>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/2005-05-04-gore-webby_x.htm |title=Webby Awards not laughing at Gore's contribution to Net Former Vice President of the United States |accessdate=2008-06-15 |author= A.P. |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=5 May 2005|work= |publisher= ''[[USA Today]]'' }}</ref><ref name=nyt>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/08/arts/08webb.html |title=Accepting a Webby? Brevity, Please |accessdate=2008-06-15 |author= |last= Carr |first=David |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=8 June 2005|work= |publisher= [[American Broadcasting Company]] }}</ref> *''Webby Person of the Year'': [[Craig Newmark]], the founder of [[Craigslist]] *''Webby Artist of the Year'': The [[Kleptones]] *''Webby Breakout of the Year'': Caterina Fake and Stewart Butterfield, the founders of [[Flickr]]
Webby Awards winners included [[Mercedes-Benz]] USA (Automotive), [[Google]] (Best Practices), [[Merck & Co.|Merck]] (Health), and [[Skype]] (Telecommunications).
==2006== {{main|2006 Webby Awards}} Honorees at 10th Annual Webby Awards included: * Webby Breakout of the Year: MySpace.com and its founders Tom Anderson and Chris DeWolfe * Webby Artist of the Year: [[Gorillaz]] * Webby Entrepreneur of the Year: Mark Cuban, owner of the Dallas Mavericks and HDNet * Webby Person of the Year: Thomas Friedman, New York Times columnist and Pulitzer Prize-winning author of The World is Flat: A Brief History of The 21st Century * Webby Lifetime Achievement Award: Dr. Robert Kahn, co-inventor of the TCP/IP protocols, the technology used to transmit information on today's Internet * Webby Lifetime Achievement Award: [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], for "visionary" use of the internet, and being the first major artist to release an album over the internet, ''[[Crystal Ball (Prince album)|Crystal Ball]]''.
==2007== {{main|2007 Webby Awards}} [[File:2007 webbies.jpg|thumb|Nicolas Roope of London agency Poke London, receiving a Webby in 2007 for designing the [[Zopa]] site]] Honorees at 11th Annual Webby Awards included: * Webby Lifetime Achievement: [[David Bowie]] was honored for his career which has pushed the boundaries of art and technology – from Ziggy Stardust to BowieNet, the Internet service provider he launched in 1998, to BowieArt, a Web site that connects the new visual artists with art collectors worldwide. * Webby Lifetime Achievement: eBay President and CEO Meg Whitman accepted the award on behalf of the 150 million registered eBay buyers and sellers * Webby People of the Year: YouTube Co-Founders Steve Chen and Chad Hurley * Webby Artist of the Year: Beastie Boys were recognized for their 2006 concert film, "Awesome, I Fucking Shot That", which was filmed entirely by dozens of audience members using hand-held cameras provided by the group. * Two Special Achievement Awards for Acting were presented at the 1st Annual Webby Film and Video Awards: * Best Actor: "Ninja", the star of the online comedy series "Ask a Ninja" * Best Actress: [[Jessica Rose]], star of the fictional video diary "lonelygirl15"
